responded: The sanitizer report points to a segmentation fault (SEGV) due to dereferencing a possibly NULL pointer in the following code block in `zend_fetch_debug_backtrace`:

```c
if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type)) {
    filename = prev->func->op_array.filename;
    if (prev->opline->opcode == ZEND_HANDLE_EXCEPTION) {
        if (EG(opline_before_exception)) {
            lineno = EG(opline_before_exception)->lineno;
        } else {
            lineno = prev->func->op_array.line_end;
        }
    } else {
        lineno = prev->opline->lineno;
    }
    ZVAL_STR_COPY(&tmp, filename);
    _zend_hash_append_ex(stack_frame, ZSTR_KNOWN(ZEND_STR_FILE), &tmp, 1);
    ZVAL_LONG(&tmp, lineno);
    _zend_hash_append_ex(stack_frame, ZSTR_KNOWN(ZEND_STR_LINE), &tmp, 1);
}
```

Here, `prev->opline` is dereferenced several times without checking for NULL. If `prev->opline` is NULL, then accessing `prev->opline->opcode` or `prev->opline->lineno` will result in a segmentation fault.

**Patch Plan:**
- Before accessing `prev->opline->opcode` or `prev->opline->lineno`, check if `prev->opline` is not NULL.
- If `prev->opline` is NULL, fall back to using `prev->func->op_array.line_end` for the line number, which is consistent with the rest of the code.
- Apply similar safety checks in the `while (prev_call)` loop and other places where `prev->opline` or similar patterns are used.

