```c
if (prev && prev->func && ZEND_USER_CODE(prev->func->common.type)) {
    filename = prev->func->op_array.filename;
    if (prev->opline->opcode == ZEND_HANDLE_EXCEPTION) {
        if (EG(opline_before_exception)) {
            lineno = EG(opline_before_exception)->lineno;
        } else {
            lineno = prev->func->op_array.line_end;
        }
    } else {
        lineno = prev->opline->lineno;
    }
    ZVAL_STR_COPY(&tmp, filename);
    _zend_hash_append_ex(stack_frame, ZSTR_KNOWN(ZEND_STR_FILE), &tmp, 1);
    ZVAL_LONG(&tmp, lineno);
    _zend_hash_append_ex(stack_frame, ZSTR_KNOWN(ZEND_STR_LINE), &tmp, 1);
```

The cause of the segfault is that `prev->opline` can be NULL, but code dereferences it (`prev->opline->opcode` and `prev->opline->lineno`) without a check. To fix this, I need to gate all accesses to `prev->opline` behind a null check and provide a fallback for the line number (as with previous wrong patch attempts but following the right strategy).

The correct pattern (seen in the good portions of some previous patches) is:
- Check for `prev->opline` being non-NULL before using it.
- If `opline` is NULL, fallback to using `prev->func->op_array.line_end` for the line number (consistent with exception fallback).

Likewise, in the `while` loop below, the dereference `prev->opline->lineno` must also be guarded.

